{"key":"post-12949197","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12949197</id>\n<content>Fill the dishes about half way.&amp;nbsp; If you don't use enough agar, your plates will dry out.&amp;nbsp; If you use too much, there isn't room for the mycelium to grow without pressing against the top of the cover.&amp;nbsp; I use 600 ml for 20 dishes.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I'd suggest using the pre-sterilized plastic dishes and pour all twenty at once.&amp;nbsp; After pouring, slip them back into the sleeve they came packaged in.&amp;nbsp; Once you inoculate, wrap with parafilm and put each dish in a ziplock sandwich bag.&amp;nbsp; Un-inoculated petri dishes in the original sleeve should last a month or more and still be good to use.&amp;nbsp;  Remember, once you inoculate a dish, you want to transfer healthy mycelium to a fresh dish as soon as you ID it.&amp;nbsp; This way, you stay one step ahead of any contaminants that pop up.&amp;nbsp; When you have a clean culture, use it to inoculate grains, but before you do, make a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Master-Culture-Slants&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noreferrer noopener&quot;&gt;master culture slant&lt;/a&gt; so you don't have to repeat the process every time.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12949236</next>\n<prev>12949187</prev>\n<first>12947934</first>\n<last>12954780</last>\n<when>1280068039</when>\n<utime>07/25/10 05:27 PM</utime>\n</post>"}